== Biographies ==

=== Marie Brémont ===
Marie Marthe Augustine Lemaitre Brémont (née Mesange; 25 April 1886 – 6 June 2001)<ref name=bbc>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/1374164.stm|title=World's oldest woman dies at 115|work=BBC News online|date=6 June 2001|accessdate=29 December 2007}}</ref> was [[oldest people|the oldest recognized person in the world]] from November 2000 until her death at age 115 years 42 days.<ref name="AP-wire">{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NewsLibrary&p_multi=APAB&d_place=APAB&p_theme=newslibrary2&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F8922A725DE38E4&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Marie Bremont |agency=Associated Press |date=7 June 2001 |accessdate=29 December 2007 |quote=Marie Brémont, a 115-year-old French woman, believed to be the world's oldest person, died Wednesday, ending a journey through life that spanned three centuries. Brémont died in her sleep at a retirement home in Candé. She was considered the world's oldest person since the death of [[Eva Morris]] of Britain in November.}}</ref> Brémont is the second oldest French person to have ever lived, after [[longevity]] world record holder [[Jeanne Calment]].<ref>{{cite web|author=AlterNet / By Mad Dog |url=http://www.alternet.org/story/11087/ |title=MAD DOG: Bottling the Fountain of Youth |publisher=Alternet.org |date=24 June 2001 |accessdate=2 June 2013}}</ref>

She was born in [[Noëllet]],<ref name="AP-wire" /> Western France on April 25, 1886 to a lumberjack. Her first husband, railroad worker Constant Lemaitre, was killed in [[World War I|the First World War]]. She married again to a taxi driver, Florentin Brémont, who died in 1967. She had no children.<ref name=bbc /> Over the course of her life, she worked as a farmer, as well as in a [[pharmaceutical]] factory, as a nanny and as a [[seamstress]]. At 103, she was hit by a car and broke her arm as a result.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/jun/08/local/me-8038 |title=Marie Bremont, 115; Believed to Be Oldest Person in the World |work=Los Angeles Times |date=8 June 2001 |accessdate=2 June 2013}}</ref> She died at her retirement home in [[Candé]], [[Maine-et-Loire]].

=== Germaine Haye ===
Germaine Haye (née Germain; 10 October 1888 – 18 April 2002)<ref name=JornalDoBrasil/> was France's oldest living person for about a year, following the death of Marie Brémont on 6 June 2001 until her own death at age 113 years 190 days.<ref name=ShortNews>{{de icon}}[http://www.shortnews.de/start.cfm?id=377083 "113-jährige Französin in Seniorenheim verstorben"], (""113-year-old Frenchwoman dies in retirement home"), ShortNews.de, 2002-04-19. Retrieved 2007-11-11.</ref> She was also the [[List of European supercentenarians|oldest living person in Europe]] and 4th oldest in the world.<ref>[http://www.grg.org/Adams/b.HTM Table B - Verified Supercentenarians (Ranked By Age)] [[Gerontology Research Group]]</ref>

Haye lived in the town of [[Mortagne-au-Perche]] in [[Orne]], [[Normandy]], western France, since she was 19 years old. She worked as a babysitter and teacher until her three daughters grew up and left home. She then devoted herself to [[literature]], publishing poems under the pseudonym Anne Moranget.<ref name=lacroix-20020422>{{cite news |url=https://www.la-croix.com/Archives/2002-04-22/La-doyenne-des-Francais-est-decedee-a-l-age-de-113-ans-_NP_-2002-04-22-156094 |title=La doyenne des Français est décédée à l'âge de 113 ans |lang=fr |trans-title=France's oldest woman died aged 113 |newspaper=[[La Croix]] |date=22 April 2002 |access-date=30 October 2018}}</ref> In 2000, following a [[femur|femoral]] fracture, she became a full-time [[wheelchair]] user, and went to live in the Mortagne-au-Perche retirement home  for the last two years of her life. She died in her sleep.<ref name=JornalDoBrasil>{{pt icon}}[http://jbonline.terra.com.br/extra/2002/04/19/e1904033.html "Morre a mais velha francesa com 113 anos"]{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ("Oldest Frenchwoman dies at 113"), ''[[Jornal do Brasil]]'', 2002-04-19. Retrieved 2007-11-11.</ref><ref name=ShortNews/>

===Camille Loiseau===
Camille Blanche Loiseau Chadal (13 February 1892 – 12 August 2006) was the [[list of the verified oldest people|oldest living person]] in France until her death aged 114 years 180 days. Loiseau was ranked fifth in the world in the 2007 edition of [[Guinness World Records]]. She achieved the position of France's oldest woman, known in France as the ''[[Wiktionary:doyenne|Doyenne de France]]'', on the death of Anne Primout on 26 March 2005, who also died at age 114.

She was the oldest verified person living in Europe since the death of 114-year-old Italian [[Virginia Dighero]] 28 December 2005, and became the fifth oldest verified living person in the world on the death of 115-year-old American Susie Gibson on 16 February 2006. Madame Loiseau was succeeded as doyenne of France by [[#Marie-Simone Capony|Marie-Simone Capony]], aged 112 at the time, though the title was first given to fellow 112-year-old Marie Mornet Robin who lived in the western town of [[Poitou-Charentes]], but was three weeks younger than Capony.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://news.monstersandcritics.com/.../article_1191823.php/Camille_Loiseau_oldest_person_in_France_dies_aged_114 |title=Camille Loiseau, oldest person in France, dies aged 114 |work=monstersandcritics.com}}{{dead link|date=November 2016}}</ref> She and [[Japan]]ese supercentenarian Toyo Endo were recognised by Guinness World Records as the oldest people to share a birthday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/oldest-living-people-to-share-a-birthday}}</ref>

She was born in Paris and did not move out of the city until her hospitalization in 1998 due to a fall. She was the youngest of nine children, four boys and five girls. On 13 August 1910 she married René Frédéric Chadal, although their marriage lasted only 15 days.<ref name="gerontoprevention">{{Cite web |url=http://gerontoprevention.free.fr/loiseau.html |title=Camille Loiseau 1892–2006 |work=gerontoprevention.free.fr |language=French}}</ref> As is common in France, Camille Loiseau chose not to use her husband's last name.

She celebrated her last birthday "with a little champagne". She died in the [[Hôpital Paul-Brousse]] in [[Villejuif]].<ref name="gerontoprevention"/>

===Marie-Simone Capony=== 
Marie-Simone Capony (14 March 1894 – 15 September 2007) was, at age 113, the oldest living person in [[France]].<ref name=sputnik>{{cite web |url=http://en.rian.ru/world/20070919/79534243.html |title=France's oldest woman dies at 113 |work=Sputnik International |date=19 September 2007 |accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref> She became the French [[Wiktionary:doyenne|doyenne]] following the death of 114-year-old [[Camille Loiseau]] in August 2006. At the time of her death, aged 113 years and 185 days, due to heart failure, she ranked as the [[oldest people|fifth-oldest person in the world]]. Capony was born in Charlieu ([[Loire]]), and lived in a retirement facility in [[Cannes]]. She never married (her [[fiancé]] was killed in action at the beginning of the [[World War I|First World War]] in 1914).<ref name=sputnik/> Capony had not been able to walk since she turned 100, after having an operation in order to fix a broken thighbone, but she still remained in fairly good health considering her very advanced age.<ref name=sputnik/>

===Mathilde Aussant===
Mathilde Aussant (27 February 1898 – 23 July 2011) was a [[France|French]] [[supercentenarian]] who was at the time of her death believed to be the oldest verified person in France.<ref name=GRG-Rankings /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://connexionfrance.com/france-oldest-woman-mathilde-aussant-dies-113-12902-view-article.html |title=France's oldest woman dies at 113 |work=[[The Connexion]] |date=25 July 2011 |accessdate=25 July 2011}}</ref> However, the subsequent verification of [[#Marie-Isabelle Diaz|Marie-Isabelle Diaz]] to have been born on 22 February 1898 meant that Aussant was in fact the second oldest.

She was born in [[Donges]], France,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://francaiscelebres.com/1898.html |title=Français célèbres nés en 1898 |work=Francaiscelebres.com |date= |accessdate=18 November 2013 |language=French |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315213518/http://francaiscelebres.com/1898.html |archivedate=15 March 2016}}</ref> the fifth of eleven children born to François Gaudet and Hélène Halgand. Following the death of her mother, she left Donges for [[Paris]] in 1923. She worked as a housekeeper and babysitter. She married a railroad worker from [[Gare Saint-Lazare]], who died in 1936. In 1946, she married another railroad worker, René Aussant, who died in 1961. Their only daughter died in 2007, leaving Aussant without any immediate family.<ref name="Oldest">{{cite web |url=http://www.blois.maville.com/actu/actudet_-Mathilde-Aussant-vice-doyenne-de-France-_dep-1012969_actu.Htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130104113654/http://www.blois.maville.com/actu/actudet_-Mathilde-Aussant-vice-doyenne-de-France-_dep-1012969_actu.Htm |dead-url=yes |archive-date=4 January 2013 |title=Oldest Living French woman |work=blois.maville.com |date=4 November 2010}} </ref> In 1999, she moved to a retirement home. In 2008 she was awarded the Medal of the city of Donges. She died at a hospital in [[Vendôme]] on Saturday, 23 July 2011.

=== Marie-Isabelle Diaz {{anchor|Maria Diaz}} ===
Marie-Isabelle Diaz (née Rodriguez, 22 February 1898 – 29 October 2011) was posthumously recognized as the oldest living French person from the death of Eugénie Blanchard on 4 November 2010, until her own death a year later.<ref name=lemauricien-20110814 /> She is also the [[oldest people|oldest person]] ever from the [[overseas departments and territories of France|French possession]] of [[Réunion]]. She was born in [[Sidi Bel Abbès]], [[Algeria]], then an overseas territory of France. She was married and had three children. Her husband died at 60. After its independence she left the country in 1962. She then settled in Spain with one of her sons. Then she lived a few years in [[Rouen]]. She lived in Réunion from 1983 until her death. She was 113 years 249 days old when she died.<ref name=lemauricien-20110814 /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.liberation.fr/societe/2011/07/29/a-la-reunion-une-doyenne-des-francais-en-pleine-forme-mais-tres-discrete_752125 |title=A La Réunion, une doyenne des Français «en pleine forme» mais très discrète |date=29 July 2011|newspaper=[[Libération]]|language=French}}</ref>

